i'm building a simplified rollup from scratch to demystify ✨rollups ✨

just finished writing the execution layer.

challenges ahead:
- replicating the state processor in pure solidity. i've been very cautious of how i do serde in the EL state processor to not use non deterministic stuff and consistently use RLP/keccak256 to make sure i can easily replicate it in solidity.

- writing a _reliable_ sequencer might be harder than it seems. need to make sure transaction are not stuck in the mempool...

- i really want to do a single shot fraud prover, but worried abt running out of gas if i replay an entire block. might have to store intermediate state root.
down!

i'd imagine this would rarely happen these days, but in times of L1 congestion there are often instances where transactions are just "stuck" in the mempool and are "soft dropped". you'd have to replay the tx with the same nonce to bump it up
yeah, it's not really sequencer issue. it's just that sequencer is responsible in recovering from that failure state.

Go 1.20 has a cool new experimental memory management feature called "Arena"  

- its a braindead simple way to have more control over alloc/dealloc in Go
- make Go even more brrr because you no longer have to deal with GC overhead (i.e. tracking objects) within Arena

how it works:

1. program creates an arena that is basically saying, "hey, im an adult let me do things my way in this contiguous chunk of memory"

2. program do stuff in the arena

3. when ur done, release the entire Arena's memory back

yum yum golang so good

I would try using parity_subscribe. It's a more powerful version of eth_subscribe that basically allows you to subscribe to arbitrary eth_ rpc endpoint.

so for your usecase, you can subscribe to both call and logs

The biggest advise I got on how to be more "creative:

Curate a moodboard for whatever it is you want to be creative at.

A huge part of creativity is consuming a lot of source material and being able to draw upon them easily
This includes software engineering too! GitHub stars is a great way to do this

I personally like any tools that let me work at the speed of thought (i.e. less structure/effort).

For images, Pinterest is amazing because it also helps with discovery and the extension allows you to clip any images from the web.

For links, I've been playing with Curius
